[src:sturm-liouville-theory/eigenfunction] If we impose boundary conditions, for example that the ends of the string are fixed at *x* = 0 and *x* = *L*, namely *X*(0) = *X*(*L*) = 0, and that *T*(0) = 0, we constrain the eigenvalues.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/eigenfunction] This last boundary condition constrains ω to take a value *ωn* = ⁠*ncπ*/*L*⁠, where n is any integer.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/eigenfunction] In the example of a string instrument, the frequency *ωn* is the frequency of the n-th harmonic, which is called the (*n* − 1)-th overtone.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/eigenfunction] $H=-{\frac {\hbar ^{2}}{2m}}\nabla ^{2}+V(\mathbf {r} ,t)$ can be solved by separation of variables if the Hamiltonian does not depend explicitly on time.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/eigenfunction] Both of these differential equations are eigenvalue equations with eigenvalue E.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/eigenfunction] Equation (**2**) is the time-independent Schrödinger equation.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/eigenfunction] The eigenfunctions φk of the Hamiltonian operator are stationary states of the quantum mechanical system, each with a corresponding energy Ek.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/eigenfunction] They represent allowable energy states of the system and may be constrained by boundary conditions.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/eigenfunction] The Hamiltonian operator H is an example of a Hermitian operator whose eigenfunctions form an orthonormal basis.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/eigenfunction] The success of the Schrödinger equation in explaining the spectral characteristics of hydrogen is considered one of the greatest triumphs of 20th century physics.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/eigenfunction] In the study of signals and systems, an eigenfunction of a system is a signal *f*(*t*) that, when input into the system, produces a response *y*(*t*) = *λf*(*t*), where λ is a complex scalar eigenvalue.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/orthogonal-functions] In mathematics, **orthogonal functions** belong to a function space that is a vector space equipped with a bilinear form.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/orthogonal-functions] The functions f and g are orthogonal when this integral is zero, i.e. $\langle f,\,g\rangle =0$ whenever $f\neq g$ .
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/orthogonal-functions] As with a basis of vectors in a finite-dimensional space, orthogonal functions can form an infinite basis for a function space.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/orthogonal-functions] Conceptually, the above integral is the equivalent of a vector dot product; two vectors are mutually independent (orthogonal) if their dot-product is zero.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/orthogonal-functions] It follows that the sequence $\left\{f_{n}/\left\|f_{n}\right\|_{2}\right\}$ is of functions of *L*2-norm one, forming an orthonormal sequence.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/orthogonal-functions] To have a defined *L*2-norm, the integral must be bounded, which restricts the functions to being square-integrable.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/orthogonal-functions] Several sets of orthogonal functions have become standard bases for approximating functions.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/orthogonal-functions] For example, the sine functions sin *nx* and sin *mx* are orthogonal on the interval $x\in (-\pi ,\pi )$ when $m\neq n$ and *n* and *m* are positive integers.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/orthogonal-functions] and the integral of the product of the two sine functions vanishes.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/orthogonal-functions] Together with cosine functions, these orthogonal functions may be assembled into a trigonometric polynomial to approximate a given function on the interval with its Fourier series.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/orthogonal-functions] If one begins with the monomial sequence $\left\{1,x,x^{2},\dots \right\}$ on the interval $[-1,1]$ and applies the Gram–Schmidt process, then one obtains the Legendre polynomials.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/orthogonal-functions] Another collection of orthogonal polynomials are the associated Legendre polynomials.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/orthogonal-functions] For Laguerre polynomials on $(0,\infty )$ the weight function is $w(x)=e^{-x}$ .
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/orthogonal-functions] Both physicists and probability theorists use Hermite polynomials on $(-\infty ,\infty )$ , where the weight function is $w(x)=e^{-x^{2}}$ or $w(x)=e^{-x^{2}/2}$ .
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/orthogonal-functions] Zernike polynomials are defined on the unit disk and have orthogonality of both radial and angular parts.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/orthogonal-functions] Walsh functions and Haar wavelets are examples of orthogonal functions with discrete ranges.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/orthogonal-functions] Legendre and Chebyshev polynomials provide orthogonal families for the interval [−1, 1] while occasionally orthogonal families are required on [0, ∞).
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/orthogonal-functions] In this case it is convenient to apply the Cayley transform first, to bring the argument into [−1, 1].
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/orthogonal-functions] This procedure results in families of rational orthogonal functions called Legendre rational functions and Chebyshev rational functions.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/orthogonal-functions] Solutions of linear differential equations with boundary conditions can often be written as a weighted sum of orthogonal solution functions (a.k.a. eigenfunctions), leading to generalized Fourier series.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/oscillation-theory] is called **oscillating** if it has an infinite number of roots; otherwise it is called **non-oscillating**.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/oscillation-theory] The differential equation is called **oscillating** if it has an oscillating solution.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/oscillation-theory] The number of roots carries also information on the spectrum of associated boundary value problems.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/oscillation-theory] is oscillating as sin(*x*) is a solution.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/oscillation-theory] Oscillation theory was initiated by Jacques Charles François Sturm in his investigations of Sturm–Liouville problems from 1836.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/oscillation-theory] There he showed that the n'th eigenfunction of a Sturm–Liouville problem has precisely n-1 roots.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/oscillation-theory] For the one-dimensional Schrödinger equation the question about oscillation/non-oscillation answers the question whether the eigenvalues accumulate at the bottom of the continuous spectrum.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/oscillation-theory] In 1996 Gesztesy–Simon–Teschl showed that the number of roots of the Wronski determinant of two eigenfunctions of a Sturm–Liouville problem gives the number of eigenvalues between the corresponding eigenvalues.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/oscillation-theory] It was later on generalized by Krüger–Teschl to the case of two eigenfunctions of two different Sturm–Liouville problems.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/oscillation-theory] The investigation of the number of roots of the Wronski determinant of two solutions is known as relative oscillation theory.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/rayleigh-quotient] Note that $R(M,cx)=R(M,x)$ for any non-zero scalar *c*.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/rayleigh-quotient] Recall that a Hermitian (or real symmetric) matrix is diagonalizable with only real eigenvalues.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/rayleigh-quotient] It can be shown that, for a given matrix, the Rayleigh quotient reaches its minimum value $\lambda _{\min }$ (the smallest eigenvalue of *M*) when *x* is $v_{\min }$ (the corresponding eigenvector).
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/rayleigh-quotient] The Rayleigh quotient is used in the min-max theorem to get exact values of all eigenvalues.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/rayleigh-quotient] It is also used in eigenvalue algorithms (such as Rayleigh quotient iteration) to obtain an eigenvalue approximation from an eigenvector approximation.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/rayleigh-quotient] The range of the Rayleigh quotient (for any matrix, not necessarily Hermitian) is called a numerical range and contains its spectrum.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/rayleigh-quotient] When the matrix is Hermitian, the numerical radius is equal to the spectral norm.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/rayleigh-quotient] Still in functional analysis, $\lambda _{\max }$ is known as the spectral radius.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/rayleigh-quotient] In the context of $C^{\star }$ -algebras or algebraic quantum mechanics, the function that to *M* associates the Rayleigh–Ritz quotient $R(M,x)$ for a fixed *x* and *M* varying through the algebra would be referred to as *vector state* of the algebra.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/rayleigh-quotient] In quantum mechanics, the Rayleigh quotient gives the expectation value of the observable corresponding to the operator *M* for a system whose state is given by *x*.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/rayleigh-quotient] If we fix the complex matrix *M*, then the resulting Rayleigh quotient map (considered as a function of *x*) completely determines *M* via the polarization identity; indeed, this remains true even if we allow *M* to be non-Hermitian.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/rayleigh-quotient] However, if we restrict the field of scalars to the real numbers, then the Rayleigh quotient only determines the symmetric part of *M*.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/rayleigh-quotient] As stated in the introduction, for any vector *x*, one has $R(M,x)\in \left[\lambda _{\min },\lambda _{\max }\right]$ , where $\lambda _{\min },\lambda _{\max }$ are respectively the smallest and largest eigenvalues of M (This result is known as the Rayleigh–Ritz principle).
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/rayleigh-quotient] It is then easy to verify that the bounds are attained at the corresponding eigenvectors $v_{\min },v_{\max }$ .
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/rayleigh-quotient] The fact that the quotient is a weighted average of the eigenvalues can be used to identify the second, the third, ... largest eigenvalues.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/rayleigh-quotient] Let $\lambda _{\max }=\lambda _{1}\geq \lambda _{2}\geq \cdots \geq \lambda _{n}=\lambda _{\min }$ be the eigenvalues in decreasing order.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/rayleigh-quotient] If $n=2$ and x is constrained to be orthogonal to $v_{1}$ , in which case $y_{1}=v_{1}^{*}x=0$ , then $R(M,x)$ has maximum value $\lambda _{2}$ , which is achieved when $x=v_{2}$ .
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/rayleigh-quotient] An empirical covariance matrix M can be represented as the product $A'A$ of the normalized data matrix A pre-multiplied by its transpose $A'$ .
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/rayleigh-quotient] Being a positive semi-definite matrix, M has non-negative eigenvalues, and orthogonal (or orthogonalisable) eigenvectors, which can be demonstrated as follows.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/rayleigh-quotient] The last representation establishes that the Rayleigh quotient is the sum of the squared cosines of the angles formed by the vector x and each eigenvector $v_{i}$ , weighted by corresponding eigenvalues.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/rayleigh-quotient] If a vector x maximizes $R(M,x)$ , then any non-zero scalar multiple $kx$ also maximizes R , so the problem can be reduced to the Lagrange problem of maximizing ${\textstyle \sum _{i=1}^{n}\alpha _{i}^{2}\lambda _{i}}$ under the constraint that ${\textstyle \sum _{i=1}^{n}\alpha _{i}^{2}=1}$ .
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/rayleigh-quotient] This then becomes a linear program, which always attains its maximum at one of the corners of the domain.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/rayleigh-quotient] A maximum point will have $\alpha _{1}=\pm 1$ and $\alpha _{i}=0$ for all $i>1$ (when the eigenvalues are ordered by decreasing magnitude).
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/rayleigh-quotient] Thus, the Rayleigh quotient is maximized by the eigenvector with the largest eigenvalue.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/rayleigh-quotient] Alternatively, this result can be arrived at by the method of Lagrange multipliers.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/rayleigh-quotient] Because of this invariance, it is sufficient to study the special case $\|x\|^{2}=x^{T}x=1$ .
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/rayleigh-quotient] Therefore, the eigenvectors $x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n}$ of M are the critical points of the Rayleigh quotient and their corresponding eigenvalues $\lambda _{1},\ldots ,\lambda _{n}$ are the stationary values of ${\mathcal {L}}$ .
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/rayleigh-quotient] This property is the basis for principal components analysis and canonical correlation.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/rayleigh-quotient] In quantum mechanics, this quantity is called a "matrix element" or sometimes a "transition amplitude".
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] In mathematics, a **self-adjoint operator** on a complex vector space V with inner product $\langle \cdot ,\cdot \rangle$ is a linear map A (from V to itself) that is its own adjoint.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] That is, $\langle Ax,y\rangle =\langle x,Ay\rangle$ for all $x,y\in V$ .
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] If V is finite-dimensional with a given orthonormal basis, this is equivalent to the condition that the matrix of A is a Hermitian matrix, i.e., equal to its conjugate transpose $A^{*}$ .
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] By the finite-dimensional spectral theorem, V has an orthonormal basis such that the matrix of A relative to this basis is a diagonal matrix with entries in the real numbers.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] This article deals with applying generalizations of this concept to operators on Hilbert spaces of arbitrary dimension.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] Self-adjoint operators are used in functional analysis and quantum mechanics.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] In quantum mechanics their importance lies in the Dirac–von Neumann formulation of quantum mechanics, in which physical observables such as position, momentum, angular momentum and spin are represented by self-adjoint operators on a Hilbert space.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] which as an observable corresponds to the total energy of a particle of mass m in a real potential field V .
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] Differential operators are an important class of unbounded operators.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] The structure of self-adjoint operators on infinite-dimensional Hilbert spaces essentially resembles the finite-dimensional case.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] That is to say, operators are self-adjoint if and only if they are unitarily equivalent to real-valued multiplication operators.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] With suitable modifications, this result can be extended to possibly unbounded operators on infinite-dimensional spaces.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] Since an everywhere-defined self-adjoint operator is necessarily bounded, one needs to be more attentive to the domain issue in the unbounded case.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] Let H be a Hilbert space and A an unbounded (i.e. not necessarily bounded) linear operator with a dense domain $\operatorname {Dom} A\subseteq H.$ This condition holds automatically when H is finite-dimensional since $\operatorname {Dom} A=H$ for every linear operator on a finite-dimensional space.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] Let the inner product $\langle \cdot ,\cdot \rangle$ be conjugate linear on the *second* argument.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] The densely defined operator A is called **symmetric** (or **Hermitian**) if $A\subseteq A^{*}$ , i.e., if $\operatorname {Dom} A\subseteq \operatorname {Dom} A^{*}$ and $Ax=A^{*}x$ for all $x\in \operatorname {Dom} A$ .
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] Since $\operatorname {Dom} A^{*}\supseteq \operatorname {Dom} A$ is dense in H , symmetric operators are always closable (i.e. the closure of $G(A)$ is the graph of an operator).
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] If $A^{*}$ is a closed extension of A , the smallest closed extension $A^{**}$ of A must be contained in $A^{*}$ .
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] The densely defined operator A is called **self-adjoint** if $A=A^{*}$ , that is, if and only if A is symmetric and $\operatorname {Dom} A=\operatorname {Dom} A^{*}$ .
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] Equivalently, a closed symmetric operator A is self-adjoint if and only if $A^{*}$ is symmetric.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] A symmetric operator A is said to be **essentially self-adjoint** if the closure of A is self-adjoint.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] Equivalently, A is essentially self-adjoint if it has a *unique* self-adjoint extension.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] In practical terms, having an essentially self-adjoint operator is almost as good as having a self-adjoint operator, since we merely need to take the closure to obtain a self-adjoint operator.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] In physics, the term **Hermitian** refers to symmetric as well as self-adjoint operators alike.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] The subtle difference between the two is generally overlooked.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] Let H be a Hilbert space and $A:\operatorname {Dom} (A)\to H$ a symmetric operator.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] According to Hellinger–Toeplitz theorem, if $\operatorname {Dom} (A)=H$ then A is necessarily bounded.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] Every bounded operator $T:H\to H$ can be written in the complex form $T=A+iB$ where $A:H\to H$ and $B:H\to H$ are bounded self-adjoint operators.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] Alternatively, every positive bounded linear operator $A:H\to H$ is self-adjoint if the Hilbert space H is *complex*.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] Bounded self-adjoint operators do not necessarily have an eigenvalue.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] If, however, A is a compact self-adjoint operator then it always has an eigenvalue $|\lambda |=\|A\|$ and corresponding normalized eigenvector.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] Let $A:\operatorname {Dom} (A)\to H$ be an unbounded operator.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] If A is bounded, the definition reduces to $A-\lambda I$ being bijective on H .
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] In finite dimensions, $\sigma (A)\subseteq \mathbb {C}$ consists exclusively of (complex) eigenvalues.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] The spectrum of a self-adjoint operator is always real (i.e. $\sigma (A)\subseteq \mathbb {R}$ ), though non-self-adjoint operators with real spectrum exist as well.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] For bounded (normal) operators, however, the spectrum is real *if and only if* the operator is self-adjoint.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] This implies, for example, that a non-self-adjoint operator with real spectrum is necessarily unbounded.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] As a preliminary, define $S=\{x\in \operatorname {Dom} A\mid \Vert x\Vert =1\},$ $\textstyle m=\inf _{x\in S}\langle Ax,x\rangle$ and $\textstyle M=\sup _{x\in S}\langle Ax,x\rangle$ with $m,M\in \mathbb {R} \cup \{\pm \infty \}$ .
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] If $\lambda \notin [m,M],$ then $d(\lambda )>0,$ and $A-\lambda I$ is called *bounded below*.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] The operator $R_{\lambda }\colon \operatorname {Dom} A\to H$ has now been proven to be bijective, so $R_{\lambda }^{-1}$ exists and is everywhere defined.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] But $\operatorname {Im} (A-{\bar {\lambda }}I)^{\perp }=\ker(A^{*}-\lambda I)$ and, hence, $\operatorname {Im} (A-{\bar {\lambda }}I)\neq H.$ This contradicts the bijectiveness.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] In the physics literature, the spectral theorem is often stated by saying that a self-adjoint operator has an orthonormal basis of eigenvectors.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] Physicists are well aware, however, of the phenomenon of "continuous spectrum"; thus, when they speak of an "orthonormal basis" they mean either an orthonormal basis in the classic sense *or* some continuous analog thereof.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] In the case of the momentum operator ${\textstyle P=-i{\frac {d}{dx}}}$ , for example, physicists would say that the eigenvectors are the functions $f_{p}(x):=e^{ipx}$ , which are clearly not in the Hilbert space $L^{2}(\mathbb {R} )$ .
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] Although these statements may seem disconcerting to mathematicians, they can be made rigorous by use of the Fourier transform, which allows a general $L^{2}$ function to be expressed as a "superposition" (i.e., integral) of the functions $e^{ipx}$ , even though these functions are not in $L^{2}$ .
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] The Fourier transform "diagonalizes" the momentum operator; that is, it converts it into the operator of multiplication by p , where p is the variable of the Fourier transform.
