[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] Although the distinction between a symmetric operator and a (essentially) self-adjoint operator is subtle, it is important since self-adjointness is the hypothesis in the spectral theorem.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] Here we discuss some concrete examples of the distinction.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] In the case where the Hilbert space is a space of functions on a bounded domain, these distinctions have to do with a familiar issue in quantum physics: One cannot define an operator—such as the momentum or Hamiltonian operator—on a bounded domain without specifying *boundary conditions*.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] In mathematical terms, choosing the boundary conditions amounts to choosing an appropriate domain for the operator.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/self-adjoint-operator] Consider, for example, the Hilbert space $L^{2}([0,1])$ (the space of square-integrable functions on the interval [0,1]).
