[src:sturm-liouville-theory/sturm-liouville-theory] Next one chooses coefficients *c*0 and *c*1 so that the combination *y* = *c*0*u*0 + *c*1*u*1 satisfies the first boundary condition (**2**).
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/sturm-liouville-theory] The values of *X*(*n*)(*b*) and *X̃*(*n*)(*b*) provide the values of *u*0(*b*) and *u*1(*b*) and the derivatives *u*′0(*b*) and *u*′0(*b*), so the second boundary condition (**3**) becomes an equation in a power series in λ.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/sturm-liouville-theory] For numerical work one may truncate this series to a finite number of terms, producing a calculable polynomial in λ whose roots are approximations of the sought-after eigenvalues.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/sturm-liouville-theory] When *λ* = *λ*0, this reduces to the original construction described above for a solution linearly independent to a given one.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/sturm-liouville-theory] The representations (**5**) and (**6**) also have theoretical applications in Sturm–Liouville theory.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/sturm-liouville-theory] The SPPS method can, itself, be used to find a starting solution *y*0.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/sturm-liouville-theory] Consider the equation (*py*′)′ = *μqy*; i.e., q, w, and λ are replaced in (**1**) by 0, −*q*, and μ respectively.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/sturm-liouville-theory] Then the constant function 1 is a nonvanishing solution corresponding to the eigenvalue *μ*0 = 0.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/sturm-liouville-theory] While there is no guarantee that *u*0 or *u*1 will not vanish, the complex function *y*0 = *u*0 + *iu*1 will never vanish because two linearly-independent solutions of a regular Sturm–Liouville equation cannot vanish simultaneously as a consequence of the Sturm separation theorem.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/sturm-liouville-theory] This trick gives a solution *y*0 of (**1**) for the value *λ*0 = 0.
[src:sturm-liouville-theory/sturm-liouville-theory] In practice if (**1**) has real coefficients, the solutions based on *y*0 will have very small imaginary parts which must be discarded.
